DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
Distributive justice concerns how benefits and burdens should be allocated
among members of society. The mainstream tradition from Rawls to Sen focuses
on abstract principles and fungible goods (primary goods, resources, capabilities).
However, spatially-embedded goods—housing, neighborhood amenities, access to
public services—pose distinctive challenges. These goods are non-fungible
(location matters), positional (relative standing matters), and relational
(connected to community and identity). Three key debates structure this domain:
(1) whether spatial distribution is derivative of general distributive principles
or requires independent analysis; (2) how positional and located goods affect
traditional equality principles; (3) whether relational approaches (Anderson,
Young) better capture spatial justice than resourcist frameworks (Rawls, Dworkin).

Recent work (2010-2025) has increasingly recognized that "spatial justice" is
not merely applied ethics but raises foundational questions about what goods
we distribute, to whom, and according to what principles. Key developments
include: the emergence of spatial justice as a distinct field (Soja 2010),
capabilities-based approaches to housing and place (Basta 2016, Dummer 2025),
and critiques of standard distributive frameworks for ignoring geography
(Shelby 2016, Dawkins 2021). The field bridges political philosophy, urban
planning, geography, and critical theory.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain provides essential theoretical frameworks for analyzing housing
justice and temporal claims. The distinction between fungible and located goods
is central to understanding why housing allocation differs from income
redistribution. Walzer's spheres of justice and Anderson's relational equality
offer alternatives to Rawlsian distributive frameworks that may better capture
the non-fungible, community-embedded nature of housing. Recent work on spatial
justice (Moroni 2020, Israel & Frenkel 2018) connects geographic distribution
to broader questions of equality of opportunity. The capabilities approach
(Sen, Nussbaum, Basta) provides tools for operationalizing housing justice
beyond simple resource allocation.

RECENT_DEVELOPMENTS:
The last decade has seen substantial work connecting distributive justice to
spatial considerations. Key trends: (1) operationalization of spatial justice
in planning practice (2024); (2) housing-specific justice frameworks combining
capabilities and relational equality (Dummer 2025, Dawkins 2021); (3) critiques
of urban segregation as systemic injustice (Shelby 2016); (4) recognition that
geography itself produces inequality requiring normative analysis (Israel &
Frenkel 2018, Stilz 2019). The field has moved beyond viewing spatial justice
as merely applied distributive justice to recognizing place-based concerns as
raising distinctive philosophical questions.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
Limited philosophical work explicitly theorizes the non-fungibility of located
goods and its implications for distributive principles. Few papers bridge
analytic political philosophy and critical geography traditions. Temporal
dimensions of housing claims (historical injustice, displacement, gentrification)
remain under-theorized in mainstream distributive justice. The relationship
between positional goods theory and spatial justice needs development. More
work needed on allocation mechanisms for scarce spatial resources beyond market
or bureaucratic distribution.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
For synthesis, prioritize: (1) Foundational contrast between Rawlsian primary
goods and spatially-embedded goods (Rawls 1971, Walzer 1983, Basta 2016);
(2) Relational vs. distributive equality frameworks (Anderson 1999, Young 1990,
Scheffler 2003) as alternatives for spatial justice; (3) Recent work explicitly
on spatial/housing justice (Shelby 2016, Dawkins 2021, Dummer 2025, Moroni
2020, Soja 2010); (4) Positional goods and allocation mechanisms (Hirsch 1976,
Elster 1992). Key tension: Can standard distributive frameworks accommodate
located goods, or do we need distinctive "spatial justice" principles?

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Rawlsian Resourcism: 4 papers - Primary goods framework, difference principle
- Capabilities Approach: 5 papers - Functionings and capabilities for spatial justice
- Relational Egalitarianism: 3 papers - Social relations over distribution
- Pluralist/Spheres: 2 papers - Complex equality, different goods/principles
- Spatial Justice Theory: 6 papers - Geography-first approaches (Soja, Harvey, Moroni)
- Critical Urban Theory: 2 papers - Segregation, systemic injustice (Shelby, Fainstein)
====================================================================
