  year = {1974},
  note = {CORE ARGUMENT: Develops entitlement theory of justice in holdings with three principles: (1) justice in acquisition (how unowned things can be appropriated), (2) justice in transfer (how holdings can be voluntarily exchanged), (3) rectification of injustice (correcting violations of 1 and 2). Holdings are just if acquired and transferred justly, regardless of resulting distribution. Defends minimal state and argues taxation for redistribution violates property rights. Includes Lockean proviso that appropriation cannot worsen others' positions. Sees strong property rights as foundation for liberty; redistribution as coercive. RELEVANCE: Represents libertarian pole in property theory debates. Provides strong rights-based account of property. Relevant as counterpoint to redistributive housing justice arguments. Lockean proviso provides resources for limiting appropriation. Important for understanding range of positions on property rights strength and whether housing security can require limiting property owners' rights. Classic text in political philosophy of property. POSITION: Libertarian entitlement theory - strong property rights, minimal redistribution.},
